[2] Cholera - Kenya
Date: Tue 2 Jun 2015
Source: Star Africa [edited]
http://en.starafrica.com/news/msf-concerned-with-the-rapid-spread-of-cholera-in-kenya.html


Medecins Sans Frontieres/Doctors without Borders (MSF) on Tue 2 Jun 2015 expressed concern that a deadly cholera epidemic in Kenya could be exacerbated by high population density and mobility. MSF, together with Kenya's health authorities and other partners, has been battling a cholera epidemic in Kenya since January 2015. The epidemic has struck mostly overcrowded residential areas in 10 out of the 47 counties in Kenya, where thousands of Kenyans live in close proximity with poor sanitation and drainage. According to official sources, 72 deaths have been reported and more than 4000 acute diarrhea cases registered country-wide.

Although cholera is a treatable disease, MSF is concerned that the outbreak's spread and duration could be aggravated by high population mobility and congested living conditions in most of the affected areas in the capital, Nairobi. Because cholera is such a highly contagious disease, people moving to and from affected counties can easily transfer the infection from 1 locality to the next.

"MSF is particularly worried about the scale and the spread of the epidemic in Nairobi due to the high population density, particularly as it is now diffused in almost all sub-counties and informal settlements of the city," says William Hennequin, MSF head of mission in Kenya. "In Nairobi, although the number of cases fluctuates every other day, MSF teams at the cholera treatment centres inside the Ministry of Health facilities are seeing an average of 200 patients a week," he adds.

Since the beginning of the current cholera outbreak in January, MSF has worked with county governments to respond to the epidemic. MSF has set up 4 cholera units in Nairobi and has been supporting 47 facilities in 8 counties (Migori, Homa Bay, Bomet, Nakuru, Nairobi, Muranga, Kiambu and Embu), that have provided care and treatment to more than 4200 patients. To ensure infection control and quality of care, MSF has provided 301 medical and non-medical staff members. In addition, MSF has donated supplies including rehydration solution, gloves, soap and water tanks in situations when government or partners had limited capacity to do so.

MSF is ready to intervene in new locations of the country if needed.

