[3] Cholera - Kenya (Elgeyo Marakwet County)
Date: Fri 29 May 2015
Source: AllAfrica / The Star [edited]
http://allafrica.com/stories/201505290165.html


2 children have died of cholera in Elgeyo Marakwet county. Aged below 4, they were from Kocholwa village. Health executive Thomas Ruto said: "We have put our staff on high alert and taken measures to ensure the disease does not spread." The neighboring Uasin Gishu and Nandi counties have banned food hawking as a preventive measure. Uasin Gishu Health executive Eunice Siria says they have issued notices to shut down butcheries and hotels that violate health regulations.

Last week, Siria said they held public sessions to educate residents on hygiene. The national death toll stands at more than 50. "Public health staff are on alert and carrying out inspections. They are taking action on those operating in unhygienic conditions," Siria said. She said those found hawking food will be arrested and charged.

There have been fears that the disease will spread after the Eldoret Water and Sanitation Company disconnected water to customers who have not cleared their bills. Water executive Mary Njogu said those who pay the bills will have their water reconnected immediately. "We have asked the firm to reconnect the supply for schools and other public institutions with huge bills if they promise to pay part of it," she said. Njogu says the water shortage may lead to spread of the disease.

[byline: Mathews Ndanyi and Sharon Chepchirchir]

